                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100211">Bohemia</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate when="1472">1472</origDate>. The book was commissioned by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102664">Petrus Freytag</persName>, a brother of the Benedictine monastery of St Mary's at <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100306">Třebíč</placeName> in modern day <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100308">Czech Republic</placeName>. The scribe signs his name, <quote>Iohannes de Noua Plzna</quote> (<placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100307">Plzeň</placeName>), and the date, April 20, 1472, in the colophon on <locus from="102v" to="102v" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>On <locus from="102v" to="102v" scheme="folios"/> is found the owner's note of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102665">Stanislav Bilek</persName> dated <date when="1602"/>: <quote>Ex libris Fratris Stanislaj bilconii Amen An<hi rend="super">o</hi> 1602</quote>. In a catalogue note dated <date when="1989-12-14"/>, an unidentified librarian or scholar identifies the family name as <quote>Bilek z Bilenberka, <gap quantity="9" unit="chars" reason="editorial"/> a knight family in Moravia and Bohemia</quote>. The word <quote>psaltezs</quote> on the label on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> indicates that the manuscript remained in Czech possession into modern times.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p/>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>A note in Swedish on <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="other"/> states that the manuscript was purchased by the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> in September <date when="1845"/> from the library of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100749">George John Robert Gordon (of Ellon)</persName>, previously owned by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/101021">Bernhard Rosenblad</persName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
